H.B. 536
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
Mar 26, 2025
SESSION 2025
HOUSE PRINCIPAL CLERK
H D
HOUSE BILL DRH50022-NBf-142A
Short Title: Physical Therapy Practice Act Mods. (Public)
Sponsors: Representative Rhyne.
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO AMEND THE LAWS REGULATING THE PRACTICE OF PHYSICAL
3 THERAPY.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 90-270.90 reads as rewritten:
6 "Article 18E.
7 "Physical Therapy.
8 "§ 90-270.90. Definitions.
9 In this Article, unless the context otherwise requires, the following definitions shall apply:
10 …
11 (4) "Physical therapy" means the evaluation or treatment of any person by the use
12 of physical, chemical, or other properties of heat, light, water, electricity,
13 sound, massage, or therapeutic exercise, or other rehabilitative procedures,
14 with or without assistive devices, for the purposes of preventing, correcting,
15 or alleviating a physical or mental disability. Physical therapy includes the
16 performance of specialized tests of neuromuscular function, administration of
17 specialized therapeutic procedures, interpretation and implementation of
18 referrals from licensed medical doctors or dentists, and establishment and
19 modification of physical therapy programs for patients. Evaluation and
20 treatment of patients may involve physical measures, methods, or procedures
21 as are (i) found commensurate with physical therapy education and training
22 training, (ii) the standards of acceptable and prevailing physical therapy
23 practice, and (iii) generally or specifically authorized by regulations of the
24 Board. Physical therapy education and training shall include study of the
25 skeletal manifestations of systemic disease. Physical therapy does not include
26 the application of roentgen rays or radioactive materials, surgery, the practice
27 of chiropractic, as defined by G.S. 90-143, or medical diagnosis of disease.
28 …."
29 SECTION 2. G.S. 90-270.91 reads as rewritten:
30 "§ 90-270.91. Board of Examiners.
31 The North Carolina Board of Physical Therapy Examiners is hereby created. The Board shall
32 consist of eight members, including one medical doctor licensed and residing in North Carolina,
33 four physical therapists, two physical therapist assistants, and one public member. The public
34 member shall be appointed by the Governor and shall be a person who is not licensed under
35 Chapter 90 who shall represent the interest of the public at large. The medical doctor, physical
36 therapists, and physical therapists assistants shall be appointed by the Governor from a list
*DRH50022-NBf-142A*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 compiled by the North Carolina Physical Therapy Association, Inc., American Physical Therapy
2 Association North Carolina (APTANC), following the use of a nomination procedure made
3 available to all physical therapists and physical therapist assistants licensed and residing in North
4 Carolina. In soliciting nominations and compiling its list, the Association will give consideration
5 to geographic distribution, practice setting (institution, independent, academic, etc.), and other
6 factors that will promote representation of all aspects of physical therapy practice on the Board.
7 The records of the operation of the nomination procedure shall be filed with the Board, to be
8 available for a period of six months following nomination, for reasonable inspection by any
9 licensed practitioner. Each physical therapist member of the Board shall be licensed and reside
10 in this State; provided that the physical therapist shall have not less than three years' experience
11 as a physical therapist immediately preceding appointment and shall be actively engaged in the
12 practice of physical therapy in North Carolina during incumbency. Each physical therapist
13 assistant member shall be licensed and reside in this State; provided that the physical therapist
14 assistant shall have not less than three years' experience as a physical therapist assistant
15 immediately preceding appointment and shall be actively engaged in practice as a physical
16 therapist assistant in North Carolina during incumbency.
17 Members shall be appointed to serve three-year terms, or until their successors are appointed,
18 to commence on January 1 in respective years. In the event that a member of the Board for any
19 reason shall become ineligible to or cannot complete a term of office, another appointment shall
20 be made by the Governor, in accordance with the procedure stated above, to fill the remainder of
21 the term. No member may shall serve for more than two successive three-year terms.
22 The Board may immediately remove a member from the Board if the member is found by the
23 remainder of the Board to have (i) ceased to meet the qualifications specified in this section, (ii)
24 failed to attend three successive Board meetings without just cause, (iii) violated any of the
25 provisions of this Article or rules adopted by the Board, or (iv) otherwise engaged in immoral,
26 dishonorable, unprofessional, or unethical conduct. Before removing a Board member for
27 immoral, dishonorable, unprofessional, or unethical conduct, the Board shall further find that the
28 relevant conduct has compromised the integrity of the Board.
29 The Board each year shall designate one of its physical therapist members as chairman and
30 one member as secretary-treasurer. Each member of the Board shall receive such per diem
31 compensation and reimbursement for travel and subsistence as shall be set for licensing boards
32 generally."
33 SECTION 3. G.S. 90-270.92 reads as rewritten:
34 "§ 90-270.92. Powers of the Board.
35 The Board shall have the following general powers and duties:
36 (1) Examine and determine the qualifications and fitness of applicants for a
37 license to practice physical therapy in this State.
38 (2) Issue, renew, deny, restrict, suspend, or revoke licenses to practice physical
39 therapy in this State, or reprimand encumber or otherwise discipline licensed
40 physical therapists and physical therapist assistants.assistants who
41 demonstrate unprofessional conduct, including departure from, or failure to
42 conform to the standards commensurate with acceptable and prevailing
43 physical therapy practice, or the ethics of the physical therapy profession as
44 defined by the American Physical Therapy Association, Code of Ethics for
45 the Physical Therapist, and Standards of Ethical Conduct for the Physical
46 Therapist Assistant.
47 (3) Conduct confidential investigations for the purpose of determining whether
48 violations of this Article or grounds for disciplining licensed physical
49 therapists or physical therapist assistants exist. Investigation records shall not
50 be considered public records under Chapter 132 of the General Statutes. These
51 records are privileged and are not subject to discovery, subpoena, or other
Page 2 DRH50022-NBf-142A

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 means of legal compulsion for release to any person other than the Board or
2 its employees or consultants, except as provided in this section. However, any
3 Board decisions rendered, hearing notices and statements of charges, and any
4 material received and admitted into evidence at Board hearings shall be public
5 records, regardless of whether the notices, statements, or materials are
6 developed or compiled as a result of an investigation; provided that identifying
7 information concerning the treatment or delivery of professional services to a
8 patient who has not consented to its public disclosure may shall be deleted or
9 redacted.
10 (4) Establish mechanisms for assessing the continuing competence of licensed
11 physical therapists or physical therapist assistants to engage in the practice of
12 physical therapy, including approving rules requiring licensees to
13 periodically, or in response to complaints or incident reports, submit to the
14 Board: (i) evidence of continuing education experiences; (ii) evidence of
15 minimum standard accomplishments; or (iii) evidence of compliance with
16 other Board-approved measures, audits, or evaluations; and specify remedial
17 actions if necessary or desirable to obtain license renewal or reinstatement.
18 (5) Employ such or contract professional, clerical or special personnel necessary
19 to carry out the provisions of this Article, and may purchase or rent necessary
20 office space, equipment and supplies.
21 (6) Conduct administrative hearings in accordance with Chapter 150B of the
22 General Statutes when a "contested case" as defined in G.S. 150B-2(2) arises
23 under this Article.
24 (7) Appoint from its own membership one or more members to act as
25 representatives of the Board at any meeting where such representation is
26 deemed desirable.
27 (8) Establish reasonable fees for applications for examination, licensure,
28 certificates of licensure and renewal, and other services provided by the
29 Board.
30 (9) Adopt, amend, or repeal any rules or regulations necessary to carry out the
31 purposes of this Article and the duties and responsibilities of the Board.
32 (10) Request the Department of Public Safety to provide criminal history record
33 checks pursuant to G.S. 90-270.96 in connection with licensure.
34 (11) Issue subpoenas, on signature of the Board Chair or Executive Director, to
35 compel the attendance of any witness or the production of any documents
36 relative to investigations or Board proceedings. Upon written request, the
37 Board shall revoke a subpoena if, upon a hearing, it finds that the evidence
38 sought does not relate to a matter in issue, the subpoena does not describe with
39 sufficient particularity the evidence sought, or for any other reason in law the
40 subpoena is invalid.
41 (12) Establish or participate in programs for aiding in the recovery and
42 rehabilitation of physical therapists and physical therapist assistants who
43 experience chemical or alcohol addiction or abuse or mental health problems.
44 (13) Acquire, hold, rent, encumber, alienate, and otherwise deal with real property
45 in the same manner as a private person or corporation, subject only to approval
46 of the Governor and the Council of State. Collateral pledged by the Board for
47 an encumbrance is limited to the assets, income, and revenues of the Board.
48 The powers and duties enumerated above are granted for the purpose of enabling the Board
49 to safeguard the public health, safety and welfare against unqualified or incompetent practitioners
50 of physical therapy, and are to be liberally construed to accomplish this objective. In instances
51 where the Board makes a decision to discipline physical therapists or physical therapist assistants
