23 …."
24 SECTION 12. G.S. 90-270.102 reads as rewritten:
25 "§ 90-270.102. Unlawful practice.
26 Except as otherwise authorized in this Article, if any person, firm, or corporation shall:
27 (1) Practice, attempt to practice, teach, consult, or supervise in physical therapy,
28 or hold out any person as being able to do any of these things in this State,
29 without first having obtained a license or authorization from the Board for the
30 person performing services or being so held out;
31 (2) Use in connection with any person's name any letters, words, numerical codes,
32 or insignia indicating or implying that the person is a physical therapist or
33 physical therapist assistant, or applicant with "Graduate" status, unless the
34 person is licensed or authorized in accordance with this Article;
35 (3) Practice or attempt to practice physical therapy with a revoked, lapsed, or
36 suspended license;
37 (4) Practice physical therapy and fail to refer to a licensed medical doctor or
38 dentist appropriate healthcare professional any patient whose medical
39 condition should have, at the time of evaluation or treatment, been determined
40 to be beyond the scope of practice of a physical therapist;
41 (5) Aid, abet, or assist any unlicensed person to practice physical therapy in
42 violation of this Article; or
43 (6) Violate any of the provisions of this Article;
44 said person, firm, or corporation shall be guilty of a Class 1 misdemeanor. Each act of such
45 unlawful practice shall constitute a distinct and separate offense."
46 SECTION 13. G.S. 90-270.103 reads as rewritten:
47 "§ 90-270.103. Grounds for disciplinary action.
48 Grounds for disciplinary action shall include but not be limited to the following:
49 (1) The employment of fraud, deceit or misrepresentation in obtaining or
50 attempting to obtain a license, or the renewal thereof;thereof.
Page 6 DRH50022-NBf-142A

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The use of drugs or intoxicating liquors to an extent which affects professional
2 competency;competency.
3 (3) Conviction of an offense under any municipal, State, or federal narcotic or
4 controlled substance law, until proof of rehabilitation can be
5 established;established.
6 (4) Conviction Subject to G.S. 93B-8.1, conviction of a felony or other public
7 offense involving moral turpitude, until proof of rehabilitation can be
8 established;or a misdemeanor.
9 (5) An adjudication of insanity or incompetency, until proof of recovery from the
10 condition can be established;established.
11 (6) Engaging in any act or practice violative of any of the provisions of this Article
12 or of any of the rules and regulations adopted by the Board, or aiding, abetting
13 or assisting any other person in the violation of the same;same.
14 (7) The commission of an act or acts of malpractice, gross negligence or
15 incompetence in the practice of physical therapy;therapy.
16 (8) Practice as a licensed physical therapist or physical therapist assistant without
17 a valid certificate of renewal;renewal.
18 (9) Engaging in conduct that could result in harm or injury to the public.
19 (10) Violation of recognized standards of ethics of the physical therapy profession
20 established under the rules adopted by the Board."
21 SECTION 14. The North Carolina Board of Physical Therapy Examiners may adopt
22 rules to implement this act.
23 SECTION 15. This act becomes effective October 1, 2025.
